recordings.rmk:
An excerpt from a 15 minute performance I was lucky enough to witness. This beautiful bird perched approximately 9m away and about 3m upon a Red Alder,  at the edge of a cut clearing surrounded by young Western Hemlock and Redcedar. It was dusk and most other nearby birds were silent. I'd like to think they were enraptured but the thrush. The wind was a light 2 knots (3mph/ 4kph) and the temperature was around 60ºF and falling.

This excerpt is directly from the SD card, unaltered except to fade-in and fade-out. I tried to stay quiet, but I do have a tendency to unconsciously wiggle from time to time, so there may be a slight shuffle or two. A few flies pass by.

Honestly, I'm feeling pretty lucky right about now.

(technical for those interested:
recorder: Sound Devices MixPre6
microphone: MicBooster Pluggy, mounted in a Wildtronics Universal Parabolic dish)

Natural sound. Birds perched 1-2m above the ground in a privet thicket along the edge of the grounds just behind a mulberry tree with ripe berries. One bird singing initially, but sounded as though a second joined in at times. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 2 kHz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Grand Teton National Park (near  Alta), Teton County, Wyoming
recordings.rmk:
These birds (Swainson's Thrushes I think), were heard along the trail to Inspiration Point at Jenny Lake in Grand Teton NP. The birds were calling to each other from lower branches of various trees that were right along the path at the edge of the water (there is a lot of water sound in the audio recording). The birds were originally heard when the sun was out and weather was nice, but the recording was made just before a rain/hail storm hit the area.

I cut together two parts of recordings here – the first 7 seconds includes only bird calls, and the remainder of the recording is an unmodified mixture of calls and songs. Apologies that there is also a little bit of noise from people talking and moving around. I do have longer recordings, but they include even more people noise.

[Here](https://www.dropbox.com/sc/st9wc1hnq65ugtu/AACsOAfKX9FjesojyoBe7ASda) is a Dropbox link with photos. The first photo is of my two friends searching for the birds, which shows how close to the edge of Jenny Lake we were. The second photo has a red circle around one of the birds in question, and the last photo is the full uncropped unmarked version of the second photo (mystery bird is just right of center).

recordings.rmk:
Habitat was mixed forest riparian.  The bird was seen briefly and changed position every few minutes but generally stayed within 2 to 4 meters of the ground (well below canopy).  Weather was warm, little wind, partially overcast.  Roughly 1 to 4 seconds after each song a short single chirp response was heard from, I believe, a different bird some distance away.  I have been hearing what I believe are Swainson's Thrush calls for several days but today was the first time that I heard their song.

Recording is unedited (some clicks between songs were removed without changing intervals).

Recorded using an Olympus VN-702PC recorder and a Sennheiser MKE 400 microphone.
